title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger 1022 Carbine Early Finger Groove (1970)
postcontent: Seldom seen especially in this condition a vintage Ruger 10/22 Finger Groove Sporter in almost excellent condition. Just examne the pictures, WOW! This is by far the nicest looking stock ever seen on one of these early models and the pattern of the grain is phenominal! The Ruger Finger Groove models were made from 1966-1971. This one has a serial number indicating it was made in 1970. The fingergroove models featured a walnut, Monte Carlo style stock with a beavertail forearm (fingergroove), a black plastic butt plate with the Ruger eagle cut into it, and a pistol grip with a black plastic cap has a Ruger eagle that some say looks like "scrimshaw" work. Unlike the standard 10/22 carbine, the fingergroove model came with factory-installed sling swivels. William Workman, who wrote the definitive book: The Ruger 10/22, stated that "The Fingergroove is the best looking 10/22 ever made." This 10/22 has been used a few times, but both the wood and metal remain in an overall excellent condition. There is some very slight blue wear on the trigger guard underneath. It can be seen in one of the photos. Other than that, there isn't any significant cosmetics to list. It was well cared for. There was a discussion about Finger Groove models early this year on Calguns. Search: 1971 Ruger 10/22 Sporter Finger Groove You can also search on Google for: Ruger 10/22 Finger Groove SporterReasonable offers welcomed!Thanks!
